40|$|In {{this paper}} we {{calculate}} and compare diagnosis and <b>net</b> <b>premium</b> rates for critical illness insurance using different {{models for the}} claim delay distribution (CDD). The choice of CDD affects the diagnosis rates and hence the <b>net</b> <b>premium</b> rates in two ways: through the estimation of missing dates of diagnosis and through the adjustment of the exposure to allow for claims diagnosed but not settled in the observation period. We consider two CDDs: a three-parameter Burr distribution and a lognormal distribution. Our conclusion, based on a single, but extensive, data set, is that <b>net</b> <b>premium</b> rates are not significantly affected by the choice of CD...|$|R
